                    <h1>The Sting of a Scorpion  </h1>
            <div id="slider"> 
             
                  
                <p>
        

I was trying to defeat the screeching scorpion <br> </br>
that pattered about the screen of my video game, <br> </br>
when I felt a chill so icy that trees began to whine <br> </br>
under the pressure of it. It raised roaming skin <br> </br>
on my neck to dance to the mutilated strings <br> </br>
of a soulless symphony.  <br> </br>
<br> </br>
And I remembered your scarlet jacket, <br> </br>
so crumpled, that it looked like it had just <br> </br>
survived a tornado. It barely braced the wind <br> </br>
as you walked along, while I burst into song <br> </br>
in the middle of the frostbitten New York street. <br> </br>
<br> </br>
You laughed without restraint  and I stroked down <br> </br>
the street like a butterfly flying to a bohemian beat <br> </br>
and we were like peacocks beside Central Park <br> </br>
and we laughed like clowns watching Carmina Burana, <br> </br>
taking the lyrics for what they were and not <br> </br>
what the opera snobs proclaimed they meant. <br> </br>
<br> </br>
But the breeze passes and so does the memory, <br> </br>
as I watch the scorpion suffer and turn to scalding ash. <br> </br>
And I embraced that sultry sting <br> </br>
that comes with being alone. It devours <br> </br>
my mind like a surf that envelops a ship stuck in a storm. <br> </br>

<br> </br>

                      
                
                    </p>
                    
                  
                
